              44.2094
            ],
            "map_keywords": [
              "Uplistsikhe Cave City",
              "Ouplistsuli Church",
              "Queen Tamar's Hall",
              "Uplistsikhe Wine Cellars"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Discover Uplistsikhe, one of the oldest urban settlements in the Caucasus, carved entirely from rock on a plateau above the Mtkvari River. Dating from the late Bronze Age and flourishing as a major trading hub in the 6th century BC, this remarkable cave city once served as a vital stop on the Silk Road connecting Asia to Europe. Hundreds of caves, chambers, and tunnels honeycomb the sandstone formations.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Explore the ancient cave city's impressive infrastructure including a large central square, the Queen Tamar Hall, wine cellars carved into rock, a pagan temple, and a medieval Christian church. An ancient secret tunnel once provided escape routes during sieges, while carved channels distributed water throughout the settlement. Artifacts discovered here are now displayed in Tbilisi's National Museum.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Walk through the Uplistsikhe archaeological complex, imagining the bustling market town that once thrived in these stone chambers. The 10th-century Uplistsuli Church dominates the site's highest point, its simple stone construction contrasting with the pre-Christian caves surrounding it. Sunset casts golden light across the rock formations, creating magical photographic opportunities.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
