              43.2836
            ],
            "map_keywords": [
              "Vardzia Cave Monastery",
              "Church of the Dormition",
              "Vardzia Wine Cellars",
              "Queen Tamar Portrait"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Marvel at Vardzia, an extraordinary cave monastery city excavated from sheer cliffsides during Georgia's 12th-century golden age under Queen Tamar. This remarkable complex stretches approximately 500 meters along the rock face and rises 19 levels high, originally containing over 6,000 apartments, churches, and functional spaces. The site has been submitted for UNESCO World Heritage consideration.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Explore more than 400 accessible rooms including 12 chapels, 25 wine cellars, a bakery, pharmacies, and an intricate tunnel system connecting different sections. The Church of the Dormition preserves remarkable frescoes including a famous portrait of Queen Tamar herself. Abandoned following Ottoman conquest in the 16th century, Vardzia remains one of the most impressive medieval monuments in the entire Caucasus region.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Spend several hours wandering through Vardzia's labyrinthine cave passages, discovering hidden chambers and appreciating the engineering ingenuity required to create this vertical city. The remote location surrounded by dramatic canyon landscapes adds to the site's mystical atmosphere. Active monks still maintain a small monastery within the complex, continuing traditions established nine centuries ago.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
