          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "First stop: Old Tbilisi, with its balconies of carved wood overhanging narrow cobblestone lanes. The neighbourhood clusters at the foot of the Narikala Fortress, a 4th-century citadel whose walls still trace the ridgeline above the Kura River. The view from up here - city on both banks, Mount Mtatsminda behind, the shiny Peace Bridge below - tells you immediately that this is not a standard European capital. The fortress is free to enter and best at dusk; take the cable car from the Bridge of Peace (6 GEL return) rather than the uphill walk.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "The Sameba Cathedral (Holy Trinity) catches you off-guard with its scale. Completed in 2004 after 12 years of construction, it rises 87 metres - currently the tallest religious building in the South Caucasus. The interior is all gilded domes and candlelit chapels; the upper terrace offers a 360° panorama that most visitors miss because they stay on the ground floor. No admission charge, but head scarves are required for women inside.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The wine bar 8000 Vintages (Erekle II Street) makes an ideal first evening: over 200 Georgian references, rotated by region and style, with knowledgeable staff who speak English. Ask for the 'Saperavi qvevri vs. Saperavi classic' flight to understand what the clay vessel actually does to the same grape. The bar name refers to the 8,000 years confirmed by the 2017 PNAS study - not marketing, actual archaeology.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Dinner at Shavi Lomi ('The Black Lion') in the Abanotubani quarter. The setting - an old townhouse with a courtyard - is reliable, the prices are still reasonable (35-50€ per person with wine), and the khinkali are the real test: fold the dough, bite a small hole, drink the broth before it runs. Eating khinkali with a fork is considered slightly embarrassing.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
              "practical_info": {
                "tip": "Book a table 24h ahead; the courtyard terrace fills up by 8 PM in season"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Walk the Mtkvari river embankment after dinner, from the Peace Bridge south toward the Metekhi cliff church. At night the lights reflect off the water and the old town stacks up the hillside. The 20-minute walk is flat and well-lit - a rare chance in Tbilisi to cover ground without climbing.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 30
            }
          ]
