            "map_keywords": [
              "Georgian National Museum Tbilisi",
              "Sulphur Baths Abanotubani Tbilisi",
              "Mtatsminda Park Tbilisi",
              "Fabrika Tbilisi"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "The Georgian National Museum (Rustaveli Avenue 3) holds the archaeological argument at the core of the whole trip. In the basement treasury, alongside Scythian gold from Vani (3rd-2nd centuries BC), look for the Neolithic pottery shards from Shulaveris Gora dated to 6000 BC - the very vessels whose residues, analysed by Patrick McGovern's team and published in PNAS in November 2017, confirmed wine production 600-1,000 years earlier than any previous evidence on Earth. Seeing a shard of fired clay and knowing what it proved is oddly moving. Allow 2 hours. Ticket: 7 GEL (~2.50€).",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 120
            },
            {
              "text": "The sulphur baths of Abanotubani gave Tbilisi its name - 'tbili' means warm in Georgian. The legend: King Vakhtang Gorgasali was hunting in 458 AD when a pheasant he shot fell into a hot spring and emerged cooked, which convinced him to found a city on the spot. Pouchkine visited in 1829 and wrote that he had never encountered anything more luxurious. The domed brick bathhouses (17th-18th century) are still operating; the most ornate is Chreli-Abano with its blue-tiled facade. A basic soak runs about 30€/hour, a scrub and massage about 60€. Book the private room, not the communal pool.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 120
            },
            {
              "text": "Fabrika, in the Chugureti district, is the converted Soviet textile factory that best shows what Tbilisi's under-40 scene looks like right now: container-bar courtyards, vinyl shops, a natural wine bar (Naturalist Wine Bar, specialised in qvevri), tattoo studios, and a hostel with some of the best design in the city. Worth 45 minutes even if you don't stay.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Take the 1905 funicular up Mount Mtatsminda (727m) at sunset. The Soviet-era amusement park at the top is delightfully eccentric, the views over the city at golden hour are genuinely good, and the ride itself - the funicular creaks along a cliff face - is half the experience. Return ticket: 3 GEL.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 90,
              "practical_info": {
                "tip": "Avoid Sundays when queues for the funicular can be 45 minutes long"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Dinner at Barbarestan, based on a real 1873 cookbook by Duchess Barbara Jorjadze - every dish follows a historical Georgian recipe. It is probably the most interesting dinner you will have in the country: not fusion, not reinvention, just documented 19th-century Georgian bourgeois cooking that most Georgians have never eaten. Book at least a week in advance. Budget 50-80€ per person with wine.",
