            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Sighnaghi sits on a ridge at 800 metres with the Alazani valley below and the snow-capped Greater Caucasus behind - a view that justifies the drive entirely. King Erekle II built the 4 km of fortified walls and 23 towers in the 18th century to protect the town from Persian raids. Today about 2,000 people live here and the whole centre has been carefully (some say over-carefully) restored. One genuinely odd detail: since 2007, the town has operated Georgia's only 24/7 civil registry office, allowing couples to marry without an appointment at any hour of the night. The scheme to attract tourists worked.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Bodbe Monastery, 2 km south of Sighnaghi, is where Saint Nino - the 4th-century woman credited with converting Georgia to Christianity - is buried. She arrived from Cappadocia around 330 AD, convinced Queen Nana and eventually King Mirian III to adopt the faith. The monastery's church, rebuilt in the 9th-11th centuries, holds her tomb and a constant flow of pilgrims who make the steep descent to the spring below the grounds, said to heal the sick. Not touristic in the way Sighnaghi is - still a working pilgrimage site.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Pheasant's Tears winery, right in Sighnaghi's centre, is the address that put Georgian natural wine on the global map. Painter John Wurdeman settled in Georgia in the 1990s, learned the qvevri method, and in 2007 launched a biodynamic estate working exclusively with nearly-extinct indigenous varieties: Tavkveri, Aladasturi, Chitistvala, Tsolikouri. The wines are unlike anything produced elsewhere. The attached restaurant serves traditional Kakhetian food paired to the estate's range. Tasting of 6 wines: approximately 25-40€. Reservation required.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 150
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Walk the full circuit of the Sighnaghi ramparts. The path is mostly unguarded and unrailed - which sounds alarming but means you can walk the 4 km of walls at your own pace with views west over the Alazani valley on one side and the town's terracotta rooftops on the other. Allow 1.5 hours; the walls are uneven stone so wear proper shoes.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Evening supra experience at the Pheasant's Tears restaurant or at a local guesthouse. A supra is not a dinner - it is a ritual with a tamada (toastmaster) who conducts a precise sequence of toasts: to the homeland, to ancestors, to women, to children, to peace. Do not drink between toasts. Do not refuse a toast without good reason. This is exactly the kind of thing that sounds awkward in description and becomes one of the clearest memories of the trip.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 180,
              "practical_info": {
                "tip": "Some guesthouses offer a private supra for 2-4 people; ask at check-in"
              }
            }
